The game handles well and I enjoy it. Spending time with my friends and trading is a great way to kill time but the death penalty is to high hours of scavenging just to die by a bandit and see all your hard work disappear. Too many players treat this game as if it were a race. It's not. It's ALL about endurance. If you rush, you will die. It's as simple as that. Those reviews where they gripe about the game being "too hard" are those that should be playing Candy Crush, not a game about survival. Those that whine about mobs being "OP" are the ones that rush. Take it slow, use your head, and you'll drastically increase your chances of survival. The experienced players are helpful if you'll take their advice.

Unbelievably irresistible. This is a gamers true love here. This used to be great game, but lately everything was overhauled to be way more grindy, way more annoying, way more punishing for new players ... in order to push way more aggressive monetization. Also, most of the useful advantages of premium version were removed (starting gear, ability to save) and replaced with a few token items scattered around the world in safe houses that are worthless when compared to 'old' premium starting gear. And to make it worse, dying not only gives you long debuff, it also removes noticeable part of your resources (not only what you were carrying, also items stockpiled in the cynically named ' safe houses'), and on top of that removes up to two levels worth of XP from you (if you were lvl31 with 90% XP towards leveling up to 32 the game will delevel you back to lvl30, making you lose HUGE ammount of progress) ... and in game with quite limited and finite looging possibilities where the only way to progress is to expend resources all these penalties combined easily snowball to put you into spiral of failure where you keep losing hard to replace resources and keep being deleveled even more (which seems to be the reason why save feature was removed ... implementing possibility of sliding into this death spiral of failure is probably very profitable) So now this game is poster child for everything wrong with mobile games industry. 1 star seems like a very generous score for the game in the current state.

content: Edit: it's just a cash grab. In game the sun has been blotted out for weeks. I cannot search and have to spend real money in order to purchase anything that will help. Changed from 4 stars to 1 star. It was maybe the best post-apocalypse game on android, now it is just a shiny IAP trap. With the last update they changed the gamestyle into a "kill things and finish quests to level up for new item craftings and perks" style game. Also they removed the premium starting set, no armor and weapons for you, no save/reload, the game automatically save on exit. That could be okay, kind of roguelikeish, but the game became frustrating and difficult. You need items to decrease your radiation level and that is limiting your scavenging ability. Wearable items (like armors, bags etc.) and vehicles brake down too fast, my bicycle broke down faster than i can scavenge for new parts. You need to reach level 30 for the first serviceable armor, until that anything can defeat you easily, except the most weakest enemies. But if you lost a fight, you lost a level (and items) so this - fight but don't die - can be a very frustrating experience, and you have to fight! But fear not brave survivor, the game shop is there for you to buy some remedies, THAT level 30 armor and experience multipliers! Btw, the shop has EA like loot boxes, so maybe you have to buy some to get the needed item. Really, i just skimming the surface of all the bad things in the game with this review. Like there is a text based encounter where your only sane option is to help a supposedly half-dead bandit, otherwise he will shot you... or kill you, because you can't escape from him and his armor is the same you could get on lvl 30. Avoid this game.

The good - you can get lost (mind set) in the game and spend hours in it if you are not paying attention to real time The graphics are much improved. The game play is good along with the original story line, which I am well past and just doing random quest. The Bad - NO SAVING of the game, and if you die being taken way back because the safe havens are few and far apart. Coins and the store, understand the conversion and mine converted correctly unlike some others. I do not like that you cannot buy specific items, things cost more in comparison and the boxes are ridiculous, why would I buy I box that I do not know what I am getting or need, The wear rates on everything is ridiculous too, I have a 1911 from WWII that still shoots perfectly yet if I shoot an AK 20 rounds it is down to 80% really? content: Very enjoyable story driven narative, with easy to learn controls and enough content to keep me interested.

Overall, it's an amazing game. If you're willing to spend money you can easily buy a bunch of in-game items to survive with, but if you do that then it's not even worth getting the game. It's shockingly easy to survive, you always have a steady source of food, and water is relatively easy to find. The premium version is very much worth the $4.99, or at the discount, the $2.49 I paid for it because you can save *anywhere* and not just designated save points. Get the free version first though

After two years so much has changed in this game. I still love to play it even after so long. I bought Day R to support the developers because I believe this game has a lot of potential. Played it for like 2 hours straight and didn't even realize how much time had passed, so it was able to captivate me while I desperately looked for materials in order to survive. I also like the mystery theme while you try to figure out what in the world happened... To the world. Although given the radioactive state of everything, and the giant craters, it appears like you've (some how) survived a nuclear attack and are now in the middle of the fallout. While I look past that unrealistic outcome, unsure how much time has passed given that there already giant mutated rats hungry for radiation tingling flesh, I hope the story continues to intrigue and interest me. For those that would like a first or third person perspective... Yeah that'd be cool, however I can understand and appreciate the simplicity of the top down design. I feel like it does take away from the immersion, however, and I would personally like to see some customization for our character, and a visual representation of how we look, what gear we're wearing, even possibly our physical state. If we're sick, cold, or wounded, show it. If we're a decked out badass wielding a cross bow like Daryl Dixon, show that too. Simply put, the battle screen is boring. I feel no sense of danger at all. I've only battled a couple rats and the first rat I killed easily with a survival rate of like 30% using a flint axe, but when I fought the second rat with a cross bow with a survival rate of like 80% I got wounded and the rat ran away. Whaaat? I guess that was just random luck. I'm also uneasy about the cash shop. It appears very pay to win to me. I don't know if there is any pvp in the game, but if you wanted to, you could apparently easily survive in this world with just your wallet. Overall, I can like this game so far and I hope it continues to improve. I hope the developers really improve the immersion by incorporating character customization.
replyContent: Hello! We are glad you like Day R. We will transfer your suggestions to developers. If you have more suggestions for the game, please tell us. Thanks for your feedback!

I wanted to play the Online mode with my friend because we both became bored of the single player mode. We both started to get really into the game. I spent $30.00 and progressively got extremely far on the map. Then one day while my character was sitting in their safe house crafting, I continued to redundantly tap the craft button. Before I could notice I did not see my character's "fatigue level" rising and all of a sudden to my surprise my character died and then the game sent me back to restart with a clean slate. All the time I had spent on leveling, forging, and surviving over the past 6 months of my life and all the items that I have accumulated over the past 6 months are now permanently lost. Most of my items were purchased in the shop are now erased or non-retrievable. The only question that comes to my mind after all of this is why isn't there a save feature for the Mulitplayer Online Mode? After experiencing this grueling setback I don't think I can continue to play this game because it is not worth grinding another 6 months to try and recover everything I lost in one simple accidental death. This game also did not even reimburse my cash or items so that I could at least have the option to start again. I do not recommend this game for people who may feel the same way as I do. The developers should add a save mode in multiplayer.

From insomnia to dislocation, radiation and lacertaions, this game is one meant to keep you on your toes. Travel across Russia while fighting against a broken country with hostile people and animals, each one more dangerous than the last, as you piece together what happened and where your family is. Hunger and thirst are factors you must watch for, as well as a level of poisoning and radiation. Unknown dangers lurk everywhere, from simple rats to enormous bandit bases. It's a world than can be as rewarding as it is unforgiving. Day R is high on my list of excellent mobile games, and rightfully so. Amazing work, Tlt. Simply amazing.

GET THE FREE VERSION AND SPEND YOUR 5 BUCKS ON CREDITS YOU'RE BETTER OFF. The game IS great but you don't get what you pay for with premium. It's a 5 star game but I can't give it 5 stars given the circumstances. I'll give my 5 stars to the free version to balance things out. I absolutely love this game. I got it (non premium) months back and played for a few minutes but had to stop. I wasn't expecting a game like this on mobile, a game that requires thought and strategy. So I uninstalled it for a while and recently got back into mobile gaming and decided to go premium and I'm really glad I did. This game is definitely not for everyone. It's difficult and unforgiving and requires you to make hard choices. This is the exact kind of game that's perfect for mobile but would still work great on a PC. My only gripe is the IAP. I have no issues with paying money (hence paying 5 dollars that's basically just support since you only get like $2.50 worth of your 5 dollars). My issue is what the purchases get you. Everything is temporary. And in a game as challenging as this, you're going to be tempted to spend that dollar and another and another and "just one more because I'm doing so well this run!" To buy little things like water or food. You can get all this stuff in game, but the temptation is there because the option is there. Anyway that's my only real gripe with the game. When it first came out the translations were laughably bad, and now the games dialogue and descriptions are very well written. so they clearly put the work in In a scale of 1 to 10 I'd give this game a solid 9. It would get a ten if it either had no in app purchases or if you got more bang for your buck when you did spend money. Honestly. I wish I kept the free version and just spent 5 bucks in the shop. Would have gotten me further. So I say don't buy this. Get the free one and spend 5 in credits if you like it you're better off.

Hello again Tlt. I made a review on the premium version of the game a while back and I'm happy to say that the game has very much improved (to my tastes). However, I did find the leveling system unfavorable when it comes to crafting. When you level up, for example, mechanics you have a set goal of 5000, but your previous goal was 2500. After you make the goal of 2500, you automatically reset in points it takes to again. This is very annoying because now I have to spend more time than I'd like to. I just thought it was an inefficient way of leveling up. Other than that, I think combat as a whole is decent but I should not be losing fights with rats and they shouldn't be able to cause lacerations unless you're talking about rats the size of Bob cats. Also a minor nitpicky thing with the cars, they only last a few days of traveling not counting gas. That's kind of a turn off considering the game heavily relied on vehicles. That's all of the whining you'll hear from me for now The game overall is the best mobile survival I've played.

Alright, so, I reviewed the free version of this game a while ago, but let me go ahead and give this another go. This game, to start, is amazing. Instead of going for cheap repetitive gameplay, Day R: Survival offers an open ended RPG experience, where each playthrough feels like a new adventure. There's all sorts of things to craft, discover, and, of course, shoot stuff with. From homemade pistols to T-90 tanks, this game has it all. The story is also wonderful, I think, as most mobile games barely even have one—at least, not one that makes you feel like you're hurrying across the nuclear fallout-ridden Soviet Union to save your family... if they're even alive. In the end, I'd recommend giving the free version a try, and if you enjoy that, then most DEFINITELY, get the full version. It's challenging, completely offline, and tons of fun for months. Giving this game 5 vodkas and a fully loaded AK-74. Would definitely play over, and over, and over again.

"The greatest of all time" LL Cool once opined about himself. I'm a 38 year 
old man who, through the years, has owned and played the following gaming 
platforms (in roughly this order): Atari 2600, Sinclair ZX 128k Spectrum, 
Atari CPC 464, Sega Master System, Nintendo Entertainment System, Nintendo 
Gameboy, Super Nintendo, Sega Mega Drive, Sega Gamegear [pre-UK release, 
from one of my dad's business trips to Tokyo :)], Sony PlayStation 1, 
Nintendo 64, PlayStation 2, Sony PSP, PlayStation 3, Microsoft Xbox 360, 
Nintendo Wii, and a few Android and Mac tablets and phones in the last 15 
years. I'm now playing games via Android on my Huawei M3 Media pad. Not 
only is Day R Survival the greatest game I've ever played on the Android 
platform, its the best game I've ever played on any of the aforementioned 
systems. That's how good a game this is! It's about time LL Cool J passed 
on that moniker he gave himself.

It's rare to find a mobile game that doesn't involve locking away content 
or implementing idle clicker tactics to push you to spend money. Love how 
complete the gameplay is, and how there is still continuous updates to 
improve and expand the game. The only gripe I have is with the controls, 
you find yourself having to zoom in and out continuously when traveling and 
searching. This is fine, but it seems that the two finger zoom control 
doesnt work when I'm holding the phone sideways and using my thumbs. 
Needing to change my grip to zoom can get frustrating when it's a 
constantly used function and changing grip can cause inadvertent inputs 
that can hurt you in game. This would also be fine if the zoom buttons were 
more precise, but at the moment they only cycle through 4-5 resolutions so 
you find yourself needing to zoom by hand anyways. I'm sure this will be 
fixed at some point, but it's something to be wary of if you're starting 
out.

tltGames provides an extremely immersive and addicting game that has the 
most in-depth mechanics and well thought out gameplay of any mobile game in 
the 10+ years I've been playing mobile games. Their commitment to 
constantly updating this game and responding to reviews and even criticism 
shows how much they care for this game and its players. My only real issues 
are that the ultra HD graphics do not add more detail to the game, but 
rather make it slightly more distracting and confusing, and missions where 
you have to get supplies and items for NPCs are not marked on the map, only 
marking where the NPC is located. Otherwise this is an excellent game that 
will appeal to anyone looking for an open world survival game.

Terrific game. I don't like crafting as a rule, and this game is nothing 
but crafting, but it's interesting and there's a point to it all, so I make 
an exception here. It has the same general aura and atmosphere as 
S.T.A.L.K.E.R. without all the run and gun...which is nowhere near as 
boring as it may sound. Yeah, crafting is crafting, there's no getting 
around it. But since it's the whole point here, it becomes an interesting 
puzzle to try to juggle everything successfully and keep yourself from 
taking a long dirt nap in the wasteland. Highly recommended if you like the 
post-apoc survival theme at all. If you don't, there's nothing else here to 
see. Pass it by.

My true opinion on this app, well... lets start with the load up, pretty quick not too long of a wait, especially if you're in a hurry or only have a quick break between work or just simply need a quick break from everything.. Now as for the loading screen, background wallpaper and first look into a new game for someone thats playing.. I think the main loading wallpaper should be based on the floor based game not a third person view cause at first it looked really interesting then you get in and its only movement based.. Now as for the difficulties I think they did a great job evening everything out based on how the exhaustion, posion, bleeding and health/food increases and decreases.. Now for a free game I Totally get the $4.99 for premium just kinda sucked without premium you couldnt play on multiple devices using the same profile even when you sent your profile to the cloud.. So heads up to thoses free to play players. Lets get into the gameplay and graphics.. First of all right off the start with the main quests to get started and the rat fights back to back.. I think its pretty addictive for thoses who really enjoy survival games.. But if your going for a higher difficulty you gotta pay attention to detail and what items youll need the most.. right at the start you'll wanna get a lot of water for radioation for food youll need to focus on searching house to house and town to town.. I start with the main quests tell the part when the characters daughter comes to him in a dream and tells you to go to the town on the bottom of the map.. so at that point I started travelling to towns and searching everything and tearing clothes I didn't need for treads and cloth and bandages.. Going south, but always made camps out in the woods where the lynx and wolves are for plenty of meet.. BUT dont leave the fat behind make sure to collect that because it does food and water not evenually of course.. youll have to reach level 3 cooking though to make the Smoked Fatback.. Helps when you arent near a save point and pretty far out with no towns.. Saved my life.. Now for Graphics lets say i havent quite changed it from the defualt settings yet just turned off the the music and sound thats it.. But i think for a floor based, movement function game its pretty good graphics for zooming in and out on the map to skout locations out. Just remember even playing sand box difficulty youll still have to pay close attenion to the top bar and how much you carry and where your at when it comes to not having enough supplies. Lets just say i think this games pretty addicting for a survivor game, there are some things I'd like the creators to add as for battles like when your out hunting or just traveling and something pops out I'd be nice to have more detail and info on the predator such as attack and the actual weapon derability when in battle to kinda know more then just to select aa weapon and hit attack and hope you dont get injured.. But anyways thats my rant for the day, if anyone has a question or thinks I'm wrong feel free to leave a reply.. Have a great Day everyone..

When you find something rare or much needed, you feel like you've won the lottery!  The map is massive and though I've played for days, I still haven't cracked all the quests.   I suggest to include a way to mouse over all camps to see what's in them, because you might drop something you really need later on, and you don't want to waste time to backtrack.  Also, more fighting and encountering animals for meat...maybe that comes later, but I rarely encounter beasts.

It's a grind machine designed to milk players money for in game currency. The game itself is really fun but you find out some undesirable characteristics pretty fast if you pay attention. Travel is nearly impossible without a vehicle, and you can't get one until you grind for hours or days on end disassembling cars with tools that break and have to be reacquired. Combat quickly becomes nearly impossible because you have no weapons and any you find are broken. The crafted weapons are really useless. The percentage of win chance is bogus. You cannot reload the game and fight the same enemy and get a different outcome because the outcome is decided before the fight begins, so I started saving, then fighting anytime I found a base. If I lost I moved on knowing I can't explore that area. It's fun, it's just.... Man I get tired of people trying to get me to ptw.

The Devs are updating frequently, the Premium currency doesn't affect the real playability (everything purchased from the shop is findable/craftable), and the community is very helpful (albeit a bit sarcastic at times ;). I'm excited to see where this game will end up when it comes out of Beta, as it's already pretty awesome!   Just as a minor negative: There should be some sort of in-game guide for newbs regarding online trading etc, as the neverending "How do I do X" can get a bit.. tiring. Also hoping for more end-game content, as personally it becomes a bit dull after finishing the "Moving Town". Perhaps a some sort of minor city-building goal? Starting your own survivor base such as the NPC ones. Just a thought.  Nevertheless: a great game! Thank you, Developers, for one of the best survival games out there! Keep up the great work, as I'm sure you will. :)  -Elfm0nkey-

Cool survival game with good graphics. The game starts out slow, as you make your way across Russia searching for supplies and trying to figure out what happened to the world. It picks up when you finally find survivor camps, where they give you quests. Resource management is tough, but its meant to be. Skill progression is good, as you learn new skills and can craft better items. Some items are too scarce (cement is really scarce, and made me a bit upset, since it's needed for most settlement builds).  Some developer recommendations: Need more variety of enemies. For the first part of the game, all you encounter are rats, wolves and lynx's. The fight system needs more interaction... All you do now is choose to fight or flee and it determines the outcome (boring, no control). It would also be great to allow users to customize the sandbox (users could choose if cities respawn goods over time, if gas stations always have gas and don't run out, and if certain items have unlimited uses like utensils). And, settlement traders should be able to buy/sell more items (a world wide economy would be awesome, where supply and demand affect prices). Looking forward to improvements and a possible sequal (maybe in the U.S., where I can recognize the cities and geography)

replyContent:
Hello! Please follow the steps bellow: 
1. Switch off the Internet connection
2. Clear the cache and game data Day R Premium in the device settings
3. Launch Day R Premium
4. Switch on the Internet connection
5. Recieve data from the "Cloud" in Day R Premium

A bit slow out of the gate but picks up a few hours in. I wouldn't say it's graphically amazing but it a good look and the many menus are unintuitive and you will be flying thorough them in no time. The map is HUGE but once transportation becomes available you start zipping around. Rivers are not your friend.. It plays out somewhat like a table game. There are no animations even when fighting but it's done well. Your pretty much managing your inventory and health in this game. Move, search, collect, manage weight, eat/drink/sleep, manage health, build and fight. Repeat. Monaughtny sets in fairly quick then it drops a part or resource you need and the build/skill trees explode a bit then back to the grind. While grindy it's also damn addicting. You can play free which I did then I bought it. Supports the hard work. From there caps are the IAPs and seem very well priced. Well worth the "door" fee. The rest of the IAPs are setup to kill the grind time but you can play without them. I ended up buying gas as I stranded myself in the middle of nowehere on accident. Micromanagement is the core of this game but it's surprisingly satisfying. I'd like to see interactive fight mechanics and more npc interactions. Maybe I haven't gone far enough. Needs some diversity. All the settlements look the same overall. Wiki is a must. There are tons of features hidden throught the game. So it's worth tossing money at and the IAPs are priced fairly if you want to progress faster. I recommend playing the free version to test the waters and the paid version if you like the game. Few more hours in with a car to haul stuff around. Seems a bit light on missions and could really use NPCs and random mini missions. Maybe I just haven't run into people yet. A NPC dialogue tree would be very welcome. Old school portrait and text story would break up the search/build grind. LOVE THE GAME! It's a damn time machine.

While this is indeed a fun game, the realism aspect of it is not only unrealistic, but completely ruined. ~ There is not a single reason for anyone to suffer from STARVATION, DEHYDRATION, or EXHAUSTION within a day or two. Yet, on this game, you can literally become overwhelmed within 5 hours. Like, I get this is post apocalyptic, but even then, why does every game start out like your character is malnourished? For the love of God, please finally be the game that actually feels realistic. In 1 day, I was fully dehydrated, starving, and exhausted just by walking across town. Hell, I'm overweight in real life and I can walk across my town easily without even stopping to take a break and I'll feel just fine. Like come on now, if I can last longer than this character who is probably more fit and healthier than I am, then something is clearly wrong.

I'm really disappointed with this game. It's just another pay to win case. I was really excited to finally have the chance to play it, but the game is very monotonous and extremely RNG based, cuz you need to spend so many caps to really progress to a steady pace. Even if you do buy the premium edition thus won't make much of a difference cuz you cannot select how much of everything you want to trade for. For instance, at one point I really needed some gas and I had to trade some caps for it.. But the trade had fixed amounts so I ended up leaving most of it cuz at that point I only had a motored bicycle. Besides, these trades are just totally stupid cuz irl you don't have a silly magical system changing tokens for gas or car parts... Please make this game interesting... Make it complete and leave the microtransaccions behind... They are running the gameplay and the survival experience... You can add a trader via quests or something to really add some extra things to your equipment... But this materializing things from nowhere via caps trade is just creatively lazy and greedy and  ruins the whole experience....

I am extremely upset that the devs ripped out the cool combat system for no reason. Now you can only attack and run when you used to be able to choose how much ammo you used as well as your combat aggression.

The combat is simple, you're constantly on the verge of dying of thirst, the menus take a while to get used to, the translation is sometimes really really bad, it's unfairly punishing and I still have yet to meet another living soul... but this may be one of my favorite games of all time! I'd be happy to help with some of the English translation and tone. I haven't even tried the online yet!
replyContent: Thank you for your comment
